ce:section.ce:para:
In addition to the aforementioned validation of N-GQDs and RHSY@N-GQDs, we also conducted SEM imaging of RHSY, RHSY@N-GQDs, and RHSY@N-GQDs + SA to assess changes in particle size. Fig. 2(H–J) demonstrates that the particle size of RHSY decreased and achieved uniform dispersion after conjugation with N-GQDs, whereas the particle size of RHSY@N-GQDs increased upon adding SA. MD simulations confirmed that the RHSY@N-GQDs + SA increase in particle size is due to aggregation (
                           Fig. S22
                        ).

Additionally, the FTIR spectrum provides evidence supporting the detection mechanism of RHSY (
                           Fig. S23
                        ). In the absence of SA, RHSY exhibits a characteristic carbonyl stretching vibration at 1735 cm−1, corresponding to the spirolactone unit [23]. This peak disappears upon the addition of SA, indicating a structural transformation. Based on these observations, it is hypothesized that SA forms strong hydrogen bonds with RHSY, facilitating intramolecular electron migration and rearrangement. This interaction promotes the opening of the spirolactam ring, which is responsible for the fluorescence turn-on response.

Subsequently, the photophysical behaviour of RHSY was further elucidated through DFT calculations, which analyzed the energies of its HOMO and LUMO. For the ring closed of RHSY, the calculated energy gap between HOMO and LUMO was 3.51 eV. Upon interaction with SA, significant redistribution of electron densities occurred, with HOMO and LUMO predominantly localized on the substitution structures and xanthene groups. This interaction reduced the energy gap to 2.16 eV, substantially lower than the free probe (
                           Fig. S21
                        ). The reduction in the energy gap correlates with a red shift in fluorescence emission and increased fluorescence intensity.

To further explore the imaging of RHSY@N-GQDs within plants, we utilized a Zeiss confocal laser scanning microscope to study the imaging of roots of cucumber (
                           Fig. S29
                        ), tomato (Fig. 6
                        ), and Arabidopsis seedlings (Fig. 7
                        , S30, S31 and 32). To corroborate the in-plant SA-specific recognition capability of RHSY@N-GQDs, equimolar concentrations of SA analogues were co-incubated under identical experimental parameters (
                           Fig. S31
                        ). These findings confirm the nanocomposite's capability for specific SA recognition within living botanical matrices, establishing a sensitive framework for subsequent SA monitoring in plants. After pre-incubation with RHSY@N-GQDs, intense green fluorescence was prominently visible in the root tip cells and mature zones of all three plant species, confirming the efficient penetration of RHSY@N-GQDs into plant tissues. Following three thorough washes with deionized water and subsequent incubation with SA, a distinct fluorescence shift from green to yellow was recorded in the root cap cells. These results confirm that RHSY@N-GQDs can effectively penetrate plant tissues, monitoring SA and enabling ratiometric fluorescence imaging across different plant types.

Owing to the superb detection performance of this probe for SA in plants, it shows potential for dynamic monitoring of SA within subcellular microenvironments, contributing to a deeper understanding of SA's physiological and pathological roles. We have chosen Arabidopsis thaliana to assess the feasibility of this application. As shown in Fig. 7
                        , after incubation with RHSY@N-GQDs, the roots, stems, and stomata of leaves displayed fluorescence in the green channel, while no fluorescence was detected in the yellow channel. However, following incubation with SA, the yellow channel exhibited distinct fluorescence in the same tissues. The fluorescence patterns observed corresponded to the transport pathways of SA within the plants, indicating the ability to track SA distribution dynamically. To further validate the probe’s dynamic responsiveness to SA, time-lapse confocal microscopy was employed to monitor fluorescence intensity dynamics over a 3-hour (
                           Fig. S30
                        ) incubation period and under varying SA concentrations (
                           Fig. S32
                        ). The results revealed a concentration- and duration-dependent amplification of luminescent signals within the yellow emission channel, correlating linearly with SA dosage and temporal progression. This dose-time dual-responsive behaviour mechanistically confirms the probe’s real-time SA tracking capacity and utility in quantitative SA biosensing applications.
